{"key":"post-7622624","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>7622624</id>\n<content>The sealed terrarium, as said above is your problem.  For perlite to evaporate its water, it must have someplace to go.  Rinse the perlite, and then let it drain in a colander before placing in the terrarium.  In my experience, perlite is the most dependable humidification system there is, and it won't flood your substrates if the humidistat or timer fails.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>7622770</next>\n<prev>7622522</prev>\n<first>7621843</first>\n<last>7642210</last>\n<when>1194824014</when>\n<utime>11/12/07 01:33 AM</utime>\n</post>"}